WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.029 --> 00:00:14.388
English Subtitle by Do My Best

2
00:00:26.129 --> 00:00:29.988
They say Japan was made by a sword

3
00:00:31.407 --> 00:00:35.056
They say the old gods dipped
the coral blade into the ocean

4
00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:36.612
When they pulled it out

5
00:00:36.713 --> 00:00:40.213
four perfect drops fell back into the sea

6
00:00:40.255 --> 00:00:44.355
those drops became the islands of Japan

7
00:00:45.311 --> 00:00:50.177
I say Japan was made by a handful of brave men

8
00:00:51.338 --> 00:00:53.656
Warriors willing to give their lives

9
00:00:53.813 --> 00:00:57.019
for what seems to have become a forgotten word...

10
00:00:57.839 --> 00:00:59.823
Honor

11
00:01:45.353 --> 00:01:49.822
" The Last Samurai "

12
00:01:55.061 --> 00:01:58.328
Ladies and Gentlemen ... Winchester

13
00:01:58.463 --> 00:02:02.807
an American leader in all forms of armament
used by the United States Army

14
00:02:03.035 --> 00:02:05.435
celebrates our nation's centenial

15
00:02:05.543 --> 00:02:08.282
by bringing you a true
American hero.

16
00:02:08.907 --> 00:02:13.178
One of our most decorated warriors
this country has ever known...

17
00:02:13.224 --> 00:02:19.801
winner of the medal of honor for
his gallantry on the hallowed ground of Gettysburg

18
00:02:19.988 --> 00:02:23.436
He's late of the seventh
cavalry and their triumph campaign...

19
00:02:23.493 --> 00:02:27.899
against the most savage of the Indian nations.

20
00:02:27.947 --> 00:02:31.829
Ladies and gentlemen. I present to you...

21
00:02:32.321 --> 00:02:35.915
Captain Nathan Algren.

22
00:02:42.303 --> 00:02:46.378
Captain Nathan Algren!

23
00:02:47.402 --> 00:02:48.047
Yes !

24
00:02:48.703 --> 00:02:49.497
Yes!

25
00:02:51.109 --> 00:02:53.660
Please. one moment. thank you.

26
00:02:56.554 --> 00:02:58.800
God damn you. Algren!
Get out of there!

27
00:02:59.288 --> 00:03:00.967
This is your last performance.
you are fired.

28
00:03:01.415 --> 00:03:03.402
Now get out of there!

29
00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:05.667
Come on!

30
00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:08.948
I'm sick of this. come on!

31
00:03:10.708 --> 00:03:12.043
Yes!

32
00:03:19.585 --> 00:03:23.157
My thanks. Mr. McCabe.
You are too kind.

33
00:03:24.392 --> 00:03:30.233
This. ladies and gents.
is the gun that's winning the west.

34
00:03:30.448 --> 00:03:34.705
I... many's the time.
I've found myself...

35
00:03:36.001 --> 00:03:39.468
surrounded by a swarm of...

36
00:03:41.007 --> 00:03:43.662
... angry hostiles.

37
00:03:43.766 --> 00:03:51.575
with nothing but this rifle. between me
and a certain and gruesome death.

38
00:03:51.808 --> 00:03:53.370
But let me tell you folks...

39
00:03:53.371 --> 00:03:57.779
the red man is a fearsome enemy.

40
00:03:57.885 --> 00:04:02.946
If He'd had his way.
this scalp of mine would be long gone...

41
00:04:02.962 --> 00:04:07.807
and it'd be a balder man
standing before you today.

42
00:04:11.846 --> 00:04:17.386
Like those poor bastards out
there on the Little BigHorn.

43
00:04:19.815 --> 00:04:22.820
Bodies stripped bare

44
00:04:23.221 --> 00:04:25.821
mutilated

45
00:04:26.121 --> 00:04:29.821
and left to rot in the sun.

46
00:04:33.126 --> 00:04:37.993
This. ladies and gentlemen.
73 lever-action ...

47
00:04:38.094 --> 00:04:39.594
...Trapper

48
00:04:41.056 --> 00:04:44.952
7-shot capacity. accurate at
400 yards. one round per second...

49
00:04:45.090 --> 00:04:47.789
Son. you've seen what this
could do to a man?

50
00:04:47.875 --> 00:04:50.881
It's blown a hole in your daddy 6 inches wide.

51
00:04:50.935 --> 00:04:53.399
That's right. Missy.

52
00:04:53.581 --> 00:04:57.678
This beauty. you'll kill yourself
five. six. seven braves...

53
00:04:57.924 --> 00:05:01.304
without ever having to reload.
Note the patented loading port...

54
00:05:01.397 --> 00:05:04.836
and the smooth cocking action.

55
00:05:18.755 --> 00:05:22.811
My thanks.
on behalf of those who died

56
00:05:23.004 --> 00:05:27.541
in the name of better
mechanical amusements...

57
00:05:27.584 --> 00:05:30.443
and commercial opportunities.

58
00:05:30.757 --> 00:05:33.629
Mr. McCabe is here to take your orders

59
00:05:33.811 --> 00:05:35.533
God bless you all.

60
00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:46.725
I've seen out your
flair for the old melodrama.

61
00:05:46.781 --> 00:05:49.653
- You are alive.
- I'm indeed.

62
00:05:49.854 --> 00:05:54.154
You minded Custer said this.
"we're going to the Little BigHorn

63
00:05:54.193 --> 00:05:58.261
since I want those weird stuff to
walk into take-up for me."

64
00:05:58.266 --> 00:06:00.644
Now many things happened.
I will tell you what else happened.

65
00:06:00.941 --> 00:06:03.116
I've got a good job for the both of us.

66
00:06:03.452 --> 00:06:06.171
God knows specially you're
gonna need one for yourself.

67
00:06:06.285 --> 00:06:07.843
What kind of a job?

68
00:06:08.496 --> 00:06:13.123
The only job you are fit
or loyal. A man's job!

69
00:06:14.403 --> 00:06:18.279
Unless of course you are 
considering a career in the theater.

70
00:06:22.597 --> 00:06:23.244
Nathan!

71
00:06:23.545 --> 00:06:26.245
Just listen to what the man has to say.

72
00:06:26.759 --> 00:06:28.476
Been a while. it's good to see you.

73
00:06:28.978 --> 00:06:32.225
Nathan Algren. I would like you
to meet Mr. Omura. from Japan.

74
00:06:32.362 --> 00:06:35.737
and his associate. whose name
I've given up try to pronounce.

75
00:06:36.128 --> 00:06:37.151
Sit down. please.

76
00:06:43.233 --> 00:06:44.357
Whiskey.

77
00:06:45.001 --> 00:06:49.101
Now Japan's got it in mind
to become a civilized country.

78
00:06:50.124 --> 00:06:52.124
And Mr. Omura here is...

79
00:06:52.125 --> 00:06:55.311
...willing to spend what it takes
to hire white experts to train their army.

80
00:06:55.412 --> 00:06:59.412
And he prepared a contract
the Emperor grants the U.S...

81
00:06:59.460 --> 00:07:01.910
exclusive rights to supply arms.

82
00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:11.436
I have an agreement with
the Winchester company.

83
00:07:11.894 --> 00:07:15.247
and I am certain that Mr. Omura here
has some concept of what an agreement is.

84
00:07:15.372 --> 00:07:20.091
Your performances for the
Winchester company bring you $25 a week.

85
00:07:20.925 --> 00:07:24.694
We will pay you $400 a month.

86
00:07:28.561 --> 00:07:31.437
$5 for each.

87
00:07:31.866 --> 00:07:36.065
and another $500 when we get the job done.

88
00:07:36.848 --> 00:07:41.196
How many other genuine war heroes
you got lined up?

89
00:07:42.497 --> 00:07:43.997
He's rude

90
00:07:44.353 --> 00:07:47.697
That's how it is here.
A land of cheap traders.

91
00:07:48.046 --> 00:07:49.191
Whiskey.

92
00:07:49.717 --> 00:07:53.015
So . who would we be training
your boys to fight against?

93
00:07:53.060 --> 00:07:54.636
His name is Kasumoto Moritsugu.

94
00:07:54.912 --> 00:07:56.762
He was once the Emperor's teacher.

95
00:07:57.785 --> 00:07:58.862
He is a samurai.

96
00:07:59.094 --> 00:08:00.397
Samurai?

97
00:08:00.598 --> 00:08:03.098
The word you might use is "warrior"

98
00:08:03.232 --> 00:08:04.844
Mr. Omura is familiar...

99
00:08:04.921 --> 00:08:06.597
with our experience in dealing with renegade.

100
00:08:06.637 --> 00:08:07.805
Does he?

101
00:08:08.355 --> 00:08:09.938
He's even read your book.

102
00:08:10.039 --> 00:08:13.139
Captain Algren's study of the tribes...

103
00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.040
was a crucial factor in our defeat of the Cheyennes.

104
00:08:28.843 --> 00:08:30.132
Please excuse

105
00:08:30.587 --> 00:08:32.296
What is funny?

106
00:08:33.368 --> 00:08:38.803
Because...
back together again is so...

107
00:08:39.304 --> 00:08:41.704
...inspiring

108
00:08:47.003 --> 00:08:47.903
Excuse me

109
00:08:51.404 --> 00:08:54.004
Excuse me.
I need to use the necessity.

110
00:08:57.247 --> 00:08:58.602
This isn't a problem

111
00:08:58.857 --> 00:09:00.661
I'll just talk to him for a minute.

112
00:09:00.795 --> 00:09:02.028
Colonel Bagley.

113
00:09:02.191 --> 00:09:05.989
We contacted you because
you are Captain Algren's superior officer...

114
00:09:06.194 --> 00:09:08.602
and you assured us of his participation.

115
00:09:08.809 --> 00:09:09.614
He'll do it.

116
00:09:10.358 --> 00:09:11.373
I just need a minute.

117
00:09:14.374 --> 00:09:15.310
Nathan.

118
00:09:17.854 --> 00:09:20.634
I did what I was ordered to do up there.

119
00:09:21.327 --> 00:09:23.200
And I have no remorse.

120
00:09:24.161 --> 00:09:27.563
what do you say we put the past behind us?

121
00:09:30.499 --> 00:09:34.738
You want me to kill Jappos?
I will kill Jappos.

122
00:09:34.767 --> 00:09:35.750
I am not asking you to kill anybody. but the enemy...

123
00:09:35.806 --> 00:09:37.179
Kill the enemies of Jappos.

124
00:09:37.555 --> 00:09:38.638
Kill the enemies of Jappos.

125
00:09:39.245 --> 00:09:42.496
or Reb. Sioux. Cheyenne...

126
00:09:42.797 --> 00:09:46.550
For 500 bucks a month.
I will kill whoever you want.

127
00:09:46.819 --> 00:09:48.385
But keep one thing in mind...

128
00:09:49.591 --> 00:09:53.993
I'd happily kill you for free.

129
00:10:09.029 --> 00:10:11.478
June 12th. 1876.

130
00:10:11.675 --> 00:10:15.099
There is some comfort in the emptiness in the sea.

131
00:10:15.507 --> 00:10:19.282
No past. no future.

132
00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:26.678
And I once am confronted by the
hard truth of the present circumstances.

133
00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:32.903
I have been hired to help supress
the rebellion of another tribal leader.

134
00:10:33.791 --> 00:10:37.860
Apparently. this is the only job
for which I am suited.

135
00:10:39.341 --> 00:10:43.467
I am upset by the ironies of my life.

136
00:11:17.511 --> 00:11:20.317
Yokohama Harbor. 1876

137
00:11:53.794 --> 00:11:55.558
Captain Algren. I presume?

138
00:11:55.659 --> 00:11:56.459
Yes

139
00:11:56.604 --> 00:11:59.062
I'm sure that good.
How do you do? Simon Graham.

140
00:11:59.197 --> 00:12:02.020
20 years ago. this was a sleepy little town.

141
00:12:02.673 --> 00:12:03.959
Now. look at this.

142
00:12:04.243 --> 00:12:07.460
You see. the emperor is mad
for all things western.

143
00:12:07.597 --> 00:12:10.411
and the Samurai believe
it's changing too fast.

144
00:12:10.508 --> 00:12:13.841
The ancient and the modern
are at war for the soul of Japan

145
00:12:13.972 --> 00:12:16.272
So your new employer. Mr. Omura...

146
00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:19.654
is bringing in every western
expert he can get his hands on.

147
00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:22.243
Lawyers of France.
engineers of Germany...

148
00:12:22.661 --> 00:12:26.532
architects of Holland and
now of course. warriors of America.

149
00:12:26.909 --> 00:12:31.007
I came when I was with the British
legation. know. years ago...

150
00:12:31.414 --> 00:12:36.569
I was soon relieved of my position where I had
a long long unfortunate tendency to tell the truth...

151
00:12:36.604 --> 00:12:39.397
in a country where no one ever says what they mean.

152
00:12:39.473 --> 00:12:45.071
So now. I very accurately
translate other people's lies.

153
00:12:49.293 --> 00:12:52.729
For 2000 years. no Emperor
was even seen by a commoner.

154
00:12:52.757 --> 00:12:55.614
You have to realise
what a treat this is. what an honor.

155
00:12:55.708 --> 00:12:57.134
This is all highly ritualised. of course.

156
00:12:57.406 --> 00:12:59.047
You may look at him.
but do not speak.

157
00:12:59.282 --> 00:13:00.438
Unless you are spoken to. obviously.

158
00:13:00.523 --> 00:13:02.027
If he stands. you must bow.

159
00:13:02.043 --> 00:13:04.016
If he bows. you must bow lower.

160
00:13:04.348 --> 00:13:08.712
Do I look presentable?
I haven't worn this in a decade

161
00:13:08.876 --> 00:13:10.423
A bit snug around the midriff

162
00:13:26.524 --> 00:13:27.624
and bow

163
00:13:28.911 --> 00:13:32.459
The Emperor Meiji bids you welcome.

164
00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:36.460
He's grateful for the assistance your country offers.

165
00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:41.581
We hope to accomplish the same
national harmony you enjoy in your homeland.

166
00:13:49.254 --> 00:13:52.825
The Emperor is most interested
in the American indians.

167
00:13:52.878 --> 00:13:55.215
If you have fought against them in battle?

168
00:13:55.312 --> 00:13:59.091
We have. Your Highness.
The red man is a brutal adversary.

169
00:14:06.717 --> 00:14:09.535
The Emperor wishes to ask Captain
Algren if it is truth that...

170
00:14:09.654 --> 00:14:15.010
they wear eagle feathers and paint their
faces before going into battle.

171
00:14:15.186 --> 00:14:18.251
and that they have no fear.

172
00:14:20.317 --> 00:14:22.698
They are very brave.

173
00:14:30.781 --> 00:14:32.181
Bow

174
00:14:40.082 --> 00:14:42.855
Thank you very much.

175
00:14:55.561 --> 00:14:56.786
Step back

176
00:14:58.765 --> 00:15:02.258
step back..step back and turn.

177
00:15:06.315 --> 00:15:10.833
All right. you little bastards.
you should stand up straight in a line...

178
00:15:10.834 --> 00:15:16.634
or I will passionately shit-kick
every one of you sad parade.
let it be before my eyes.

179
00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:19.925
Well done. Sergeant.

180
00:15:20.091 --> 00:15:23.430
When you understand the language.
everything falls into place.

181
00:15:23.567 --> 00:15:26.877
The first rank kneel.
rifles at the ready.

182
00:15:28.242 --> 00:15:29.457
The second rank...

183
00:15:29.582 --> 00:15:35.204
July 27th. 1876. For six months of
work. I'm to receive...

184
00:15:35.261 --> 00:15:40.525
...3 years of Captain's pay.
teaching oriental soldiers.

185
00:15:42.191 --> 00:15:44.533
They are army of conscripts...

186
00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:47.756
most of them are peasants.
who have never seen a gun.

187
00:15:48.005 --> 00:15:49.211
Fire! Ute!

188
00:15:50.319 --> 00:15:52.720
They are led by General Hasegawa...

189
00:15:52.828 --> 00:15:57.320
a man of small stature and nonetheless
commanding enormous respect.

190
00:15:57.419 --> 00:16:00.016
What can General tell me
about this man. this samurai...

191
00:16:00.170 --> 00:16:02.258
-Katsumoto.

192
00:16:06.409 --> 00:16:09.583
He seems to have great knowledge
of Katsumoto. his rebellion.

193
00:16:09.795 --> 00:16:12.834
I'll count on his help
when facing this samurai.

194
00:16:12.859 --> 00:16:14.186
Who supplys their weapons?

195
00:16:22.406 --> 00:16:26.634
Katsumoto no longer dishonours
himself by using firearms.

196
00:16:26.756 --> 00:16:28.453
He uses no firearms?

197
00:16:28.570 --> 00:16:32.204
To those who honor the old ways.
Katsumoto is a hero.

198
00:16:32.259 --> 00:16:34.035
How well does he know this man?

199
00:16:34.041 --> 00:16:36.860
Well. the General and Katsumoto
fought together for the Emperor.

200
00:16:36.924 --> 00:16:39.307
He fought with the samurai?

201
00:16:41.129 --> 00:16:42.645
He is a samurai.

202
00:16:48.318 --> 00:16:53.471
You must understand Katsumoto
pledged the sword to defend the Emperor.

203
00:16:53.566 --> 00:16:56.053
They say the samurai's sword is his soul.

204
00:16:56.148 --> 00:16:58.110
They are paradoxical people. samurai.

205
00:16:58.111 --> 00:17:00.011
I've tried to write a book about them for years...

206
00:17:00.027 --> 00:17:01.393
but I seeked in vain to approach them close

207
00:17:01.439 --> 00:17:03.731
The bastards still wear armor.

208
00:17:03.994 --> 00:17:07.461
Yes. when the Irish were still
comporting themselves in loincloths

209
00:17:07.467 --> 00:17:10.839
These chaps were already the most
sophisticated warriors on earth.

210
00:17:10.915 --> 00:17:13.444
I need more detailed
information of their battle tactics.

211
00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:16.619
I have several more books
just waiting to be translated.

212
00:17:16.676 --> 00:17:18.645
Our captain will be speaking the
lingo in no time.

213
00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:21.056
You should hear him
blather on in Blackfoot.

214
00:17:21.161 --> 00:17:25.655
Really? A fellow linguist?
Oh. Capital!

215
00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:28.922
Oh come on Sir.
a word or two in the savage tongue.

216
00:17:29.218 --> 00:17:32.198
Just "hello" or "Goodbye''.

217
00:17:32.199 --> 00:17:37.099
No.No.."Cut his tongue out and boil him in the oil".

218
00:17:37.328 --> 00:17:41.420
Early day tomorrow. Captaindarlin'
so it is bed time. isn't it?

219
00:17:41.458 --> 00:17:47.174
I've always had a dread fascination with scalping.
I've never understood its technique.

220
00:17:51.980 --> 00:17:55.828
Imagine someone who hates you
with the uppermost intensity.

221
00:17:56.394 --> 00:18:01.149
Grabbing a handful of your hair
while you are lying prostrate and helpless.

222
00:18:06.946 --> 00:18:11.012
And scraping a dull blade of
a rusted knife on your scalp...

223
00:18:11.197 --> 00:18:13.181
with the soulless emotion.

224
00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:15.602
and let your imagination grasp

225
00:18:15.628 --> 00:18:22.357
you can. Mr. Graham.
the effect of a strong. quick
jerk-out on the turf of your hair.

226
00:18:22.358 --> 00:18:27.178
to loosen clinging part.
of course you have. of your nervous system.

227
00:18:30.791 --> 00:18:33.979
You will have some idea of
what the hell it is to be scalped.

228
00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:35.980
Mr. Graham.

229
00:18:42.489 --> 00:18:45.823
How soon can you translate those books?

230
00:18:47.326 --> 00:18:49.070
Right away.

231
00:18:50.755 --> 00:18:54.791
Just delighted to do it.
you're taking such interest in Samurai.

232
00:18:54.838 --> 00:18:59.018
I don't give a damn about the Samurai.
I want to know my enemy.

233
00:18:59.139 --> 00:19:01.506
I shall not sleep until it is done.

234
00:19:02.693 --> 00:19:05.839
Ah... foggy

235
00:19:06.829 --> 00:19:07.738
Have a good night.

236
00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:11.224
Can I get your answer?

237
00:19:11.309 --> 00:19:13.799
This is a punitive expedition. Captain.

238
00:19:13.806 --> 00:19:16.639
Colonel Bagley. these people have
nothing to do with the raids.

239
00:19:16.670 --> 00:19:17.207
Good night. Sir.

240
00:19:17.304 --> 00:19:19.608
Quietly now. boys.

241
00:20:04.067 --> 00:20:06.002
Fire!

242
00:20:15.294 --> 00:20:18.996
I suppose we should be grateful
they will fire in the same direction.

243
00:20:19.161 --> 00:20:21.129
could not put it better myself. Sir.

244
00:20:24.957 --> 00:20:27.989
Rifle butt against your shoulder.

245
00:20:29.874 --> 00:20:34.443
Eye down the sight. now slowly...

246
00:20:34.544 --> 00:20:35.544
Ute! [Japanese] (Fire!)

247
00:20:39.384 --> 00:20:41.939
Well done.
You've got that done.

248
00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:42.819
Nathan...

249
00:20:47.790 --> 00:20:50.374
Katsumoto has attacked the railroad
at the border of his province.

250
00:20:50.378 --> 00:20:54.141
we cannot govern a country
in which we cannot travel freely.

251
00:20:54.198 --> 00:20:55.606
He must be stopped now.

252
00:20:55.762 --> 00:20:59.482
My railroad is a priority for this country.

253
00:20:59.564 --> 00:21:01.039
They are not ready.

254
00:21:01.157 --> 00:21:03.039
The rebels don't have a single rifle.

255
00:21:03.187 --> 00:21:05.300
They're savages with bows and arrows.

256
00:21:05.315 --> 00:21:08.580
whose sole occupation for the
last 1.000 years has been war.

257
00:21:08.865 --> 00:21:12.601
You have superior fire power and a larger force.

258
00:21:13.382 --> 00:21:16.411
I am ordering your regiment to
move against the rebel Katsumoto.

259
00:21:16.416 --> 00:21:18.853
You will track him down and engage him.

260
00:21:22.747 --> 00:21:24.090
Load

261
00:21:25.005 --> 00:21:25.561
Mr. Graham...

262
00:21:26.356 --> 00:21:28.418
tell this man to fire at me.

263
00:21:28.549 --> 00:21:29.913
I beg your pardon?

264
00:21:30.328 --> 00:21:33.722
Tell this man if he does not shoot me...

265
00:21:33.816 --> 00:21:36.035
I will kill him.

266
00:21:36.143 --> 00:21:38.545
Captain. if we might have a word...

267
00:21:38.547 --> 00:21:39.894
Tell him.

268
00:21:41.195 --> 00:21:42.395
Tell him

269
00:21:43.296 --> 00:21:44.996
Time to get it up.

270
00:21:45.596 --> 00:21:47.696
Shoot him!

271
00:21:48.897 --> 00:21:50.897
Load.

272
00:21:51.798 --> 00:21:53.898
Shoot him!

273
00:21:54.399 --> 00:21:56.499
Load

274
00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:00.689
Faster!

275
00:22:01.710 --> 00:22:02.717
Faster!

276
00:22:07.669 --> 00:22:10.304
Shoot me. damn it!

277
00:22:14.615 --> 00:22:15.321
Fire!

278
00:22:17.927 --> 00:22:18.734
Fire!

279
00:22:18.835 --> 00:22:21.835
Ute! Ute! [Japanese] (Fire!)

280
00:22:45.773 --> 00:22:48.707
They are not ready.

281
00:22:50.108 --> 00:22:53.808
The regiment leaves at 6:00 A.M.

282
00:23:23.720 --> 00:23:27.506
1.000 miles of rail track laid in
less than 2 years.

283
00:23:27.571 --> 00:23:29.301
It's astonished.

284
00:23:29.566 --> 00:23:31.700
Omura owns all of this?

285
00:23:31.723 --> 00:23:35.281
As soon as we exempt
with the Samurai. Oh yes.

286
00:23:35.352 --> 00:23:37.714
How do you intend to find Katsumoto?

287
00:23:37.884 --> 00:23:40.393
Don't worry. Mr. Graham.
I assure you...

288
00:23:40.418 --> 00:23:42.364
he will find us.

289
00:23:51.258 --> 00:23:53.191
Move!

290
00:23:53.272 --> 00:23:54.138
Hold your position!

291
00:23:54.235 --> 00:23:56.445
Yoshino Province. 1876.

292
00:23:56.487 --> 00:23:58.375
First Company. follow up the back line around me!

293
00:24:00.955 --> 00:24:03.065
Second Company. follow up
First Company.

294
00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:05.534
Third and Fourth Company follow up!

295
00:24:05.571 --> 00:24:08.061
Fill it on my command!

296
00:24:08.119 --> 00:24:12.164
- Where is Hasegawa?
- Unclear. he refused to fight against Katsumoto.

297
00:24:14.915 --> 00:24:16.436
- Come on now!
- Captain Algren...

298
00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:19.747
we are not here as combatants.

299
00:24:19.898 --> 00:24:21.161
Then who's gonna lead these men?

300
00:24:21.218 --> 00:24:24.004
Their own officers. for Chris sake.
let's move to the rear.

301
00:24:24.117 --> 00:24:25.401
We'll be there presently

302
00:24:25.402 --> 00:24:26.402
Fix bayonet.

303
00:24:26.403 --> 00:24:28.003
Fix bayonet.

304
00:24:28.004 --> 00:24:30.004
Chakken!
(Fix bayonet!)

305
00:24:31.051 --> 00:24:34.636
- Mr. Graham. you'll accompany me to the rear. okay?
- Of course.

306
00:24:40.275 --> 00:24:41.896
Sergeant Gant. report to the rear.

307
00:24:41.970 --> 00:24:44.338
See to the disposition of the supply train.

308
00:24:45.708 --> 00:24:47.261
Sergeant Gant. did you hear my order?

309
00:24:47.298 --> 00:24:48.193
Aye. I did hear it. Sir.

310
00:24:48.439 --> 00:24:49.673
Good. then you will obey it.

311
00:24:49.674 --> 00:24:50.274
Now!

312
00:24:50.358 --> 00:24:54.738
No disrespect intended. Sir.
but shove it up your arse.

313
00:24:59.732 --> 00:25:01.613
- Load!
- Load!

314
00:25:29.733 --> 00:25:32.133
Samurai come.

315
00:25:32.834 --> 00:25:35.078
You will be fine. son.

316
00:25:52.878 --> 00:25:55.854
- Assume firing position!
- Assume firing position!

317
00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:11.371
Fire on my order only!

318
00:26:32.585 --> 00:26:34.320
Hold your fire!

319
00:26:34.421 --> 00:26:36.721
Hold your fire!

320
00:26:43.214 --> 00:26:45.481
Reload!

321
00:26:49.082 --> 00:26:51.082
Hold the line!

322
00:26:52.483 --> 00:26:54.083
Fire at will.

323
00:27:10.484 --> 00:27:13.530
Translate it: Fall back!

324
00:27:54.988 --> 00:27:56.645
Gant!

325
00:29:36.862 --> 00:29:38.946
He's mine.

326
00:30:05.654 --> 00:30:07.050
Stop!

327
00:30:14.952 --> 00:30:16.958
Take him away.

328
00:32:23.708 --> 00:32:25.942
What is your name?

329
00:32:27.253 --> 00:32:30.085
Insolent swine! Answer!

330
00:32:41.895 --> 00:32:43.308
Leave him be.

331
00:32:52.526 --> 00:32:54.758
This is my son's village.

332
00:32:54.883 --> 00:32:57.198
We are deep in the mountains
and the winter is coming.

333
00:32:57.276 --> 00:32:59.044
You cannot escape.

334
00:33:01.041 --> 00:33:02.957
Jolly good.

335
00:35:06.884 --> 00:35:09.732
My Lord. why do you spare the barbarian?

336
00:35:09.926 --> 00:35:12.393
He is ashamed in defeat.

337
00:35:12.939 --> 00:35:14.781
He should kill himself.

338
00:35:14.848 --> 00:35:17.413
This is not their custom.

339
00:35:21.377 --> 00:35:22.423
Then...

340
00:35:23.549 --> 00:35:25.193
...I will kill him.

341
00:35:25.610 --> 00:35:26.915
Father...

342
00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:29.118
I don't think...

343
00:35:31.659 --> 00:35:32.742
Ujio...

344
00:35:33.556 --> 00:35:35.853
...there will be plenty of killing to come.

345
00:35:36.476 --> 00:35:37.260
For now...

346
00:35:37.575 --> 00:35:40.370
...we will learn about our new enemy.

347
00:35:41.044 --> 00:35:42.761
Keep him alive.

348
00:35:51.644 --> 00:35:53.696
He's in bad shape.

349
00:35:55.231 --> 00:35:56.318
Sake...

350
00:35:57.667 --> 00:35:58.863
Sake?

351
00:35:59.703 --> 00:36:02.048
Sake...

352
00:36:09.321 --> 00:36:10.737
Sake...

353
00:36:10.848 --> 00:36:12.683
Taka will take care of you.

354
00:36:12.778 --> 00:36:14.562
Sake...

355
00:37:13.065 --> 00:37:15.321
Sake...

356
00:37:18.140 --> 00:37:19.236
Sake...

357
00:37:19.338 --> 00:37:22.319
Let him drink. aunt.

358
00:37:22.460 --> 00:37:24.155
No. That will not do.

359
00:37:24.251 --> 00:37:25.515
This is my village.

360
00:37:25.721 --> 00:37:28.359
This is my house.

361
00:37:33.222 --> 00:37:36.086
Please...sake..

362
00:37:44.987 --> 00:37:47.787
Sugay!

363
00:37:54.289 --> 00:37:56.989
No!

364
00:37:58.390 --> 00:38:01.190
No!

365
00:38:04.064 --> 00:38:07.891
I told you!

366
00:38:59.718 --> 00:39:01.922
Morning.

367
00:40:52.296 --> 00:40:53.153
Over there.

368
00:40:53.389 --> 00:40:54.673
Over there!

369
00:40:58.713 --> 00:41:00.697
What's your name?

370
00:41:00.798 --> 00:41:02.198
You have a name. don't you?

371
00:41:02.298 --> 00:41:03.698
Name?

372
00:41:03.999 --> 00:41:05.799
Namai?

373
00:41:06.736 --> 00:41:09.587
You don't know what I'm saying. do you?

374
00:41:10.665 --> 00:41:13.489
I know why you don't talk.

375
00:41:13.886 --> 00:41:18.463
You're angry. You're angry
because I make you wear a dress.

376
00:41:20.315 --> 00:41:21.979
Son of a bitch.

377
00:42:00.698 --> 00:42:05.265
This temple was built by my
family 1.000 years ago.

378
00:42:06.754 --> 00:42:08.863
My name is Katsumoto.

379
00:42:09.365 --> 00:42:12.161
What is your name?

380
00:42:17.909 --> 00:42:21.339
Are my words not correct?

381
00:42:25.677 --> 00:42:28.519
I will practise my English with you...

382
00:42:29.632 --> 00:42:32.474
if you would honor me...

383
00:42:33.247 --> 00:42:37.027
You keep me alive just to speak English?

384
00:42:37.482 --> 00:42:39.417
What do you want?

385
00:42:40.766 --> 00:42:43.297
To know my enemy.

386
00:42:43.576 --> 00:42:46.341
I've seen what you did to your enemies.

387
00:42:46.423 --> 00:42:48.925
The warriors in your country do not kill?

388
00:42:48.932 --> 00:42:52.714
They don't cut the heads off
to defeat the kneeling men.

389
00:42:52.928 --> 00:42:57.380
General Hasegawa asked me to help him end his life.

390
00:42:58.050 --> 00:43:01.990
A samurai cannot stand the shame of defeat.

391
00:43:02.228 --> 00:43:05.342
I was honored to cut off his head.

392
00:43:07.562 --> 00:43:10.725
Many of our customs seem strange to you...

393
00:43:10.803 --> 00:43:13.477
and the same is true of yours.

394
00:43:13.478 --> 00:43:14.578
For example...

395
00:43:14.644 --> 00:43:20.777
Not to introduce yourself is considered
extremely rude. even among enemies.

396
00:43:25.851 --> 00:43:28.267
Nathan Algren.

397
00:43:30.603 --> 00:43:32.194
I am honored to meet you.

398
00:43:33.603 --> 00:43:36.621
I have enjoyed this conversation in English.

399
00:43:36.757 --> 00:43:38.182
I have questions.

400
00:43:38.237 --> 00:43:43.984
I have introduced myself.
you have introduced yourself.
This is a very good conversation.

401
00:43:44.477 --> 00:43:45.610
I have questions!

402
00:43:45.657 --> 00:43:49.023
- Questions come later.
- Who was the warrior in the red armor?

403
00:43:49.367 --> 00:43:52.412
My brother-in-law. Hirotaro.

404
00:43:52.469 --> 00:43:53.953
and the woman who cares for me?

405
00:43:54.051 --> 00:43:58.406
My sister. Hirotaro's wife.
Her name is Taka.

406
00:43:58.577 --> 00:44:00.943
I killed her husband?

407
00:44:01.874 --> 00:44:03.926
It was a good death!

408
00:44:17.674 --> 00:44:22.724
You! Come... please...

409
00:44:51.995 --> 00:44:53.411
Thank you.

410
00:44:54.112 --> 00:44:56.412
Douzo! [Japanese] (please!)

411
00:45:01.996 --> 00:45:05.933
He smells like the pigs. Tell my
brother I cannot stand this.

412
00:45:06.080 --> 00:45:07.414
Why don't you tell him?

413
00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:09.523
At least make him take a bath.

414
00:46:15.414 --> 00:46:17.424
Nicely done!

415
00:46:20.025 --> 00:46:22.961
They may be children.
but they are strong.

416
00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:24.556
You try.

417
00:46:25.057 --> 00:46:26.357
Fight!

418
00:46:45.405 --> 00:46:46.905
Muyamini [Japanese]
(How absurd you are!)

419
00:47:06.806 --> 00:47:08.742
Put down the sword.

420
00:47:13.143 --> 00:47:14.543
Drop it!

421
00:49:35.678 --> 00:49:37.339
I just realised...

422
00:49:37.593 --> 00:49:39.323
I've been remiss. Forgive me I...

423
00:49:39.424 --> 00:49:44.024
forget to thank you for
looking out for me yesterday.

424
00:49:44.214 --> 00:49:46.345
It's your job. correct?

425
00:49:46.529 --> 00:49:48.255
Protecting me.

426
00:49:49.311 --> 00:49:54.462
Well done. "Bob".
You don't mind if I call you "Bobby"?

427
00:49:54.515 --> 00:49:56.726
I knew a Bob once.

428
00:49:56.730 --> 00:49:58.181
God. he's a grist mill.

429
00:49:59.222 --> 00:50:02.050
You hear this man. Bob?

430
00:50:05.294 --> 00:50:09.610
Ujio is teaching you
the way of Japanese sword.

431
00:50:10.807 --> 00:50:13.345
Yes. indeed.

432
00:50:14.809 --> 00:50:18.436
You fought against the red indians?

433
00:50:23.279 --> 00:50:24.495
Yes.

434
00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:26.906
Tell me of your part in this war.

435
00:50:27.002 --> 00:50:28.386
- Why?
- I wish to learn.

436
00:50:28.462 --> 00:50:29.775
Read a book.

437
00:50:29.872 --> 00:50:31.902
I'd rather have a good conversation.

438
00:50:31.942 --> 00:50:33.312
- Why?
- Because...

439
00:50:33.856 --> 00:50:37.393
we are both students of war

440
00:50:43.150 --> 00:50:44.215
So...

441
00:50:46.270 --> 00:50:49.427
you were the General of your army?

442
00:50:51.158 --> 00:50:56.242
No... I was a Captain.

443
00:50:56.288 --> 00:50:59.035
This is a low rank?

444
00:51:00.636 --> 00:51:02.336
a middle rank

445
00:51:03.713 --> 00:51:05.997
Then who was the General?

446
00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:13.164
Don't you have a rebellion to lead?

447
00:51:13.238 --> 00:51:16.586
People in your country do not like conversation?

448
00:51:16.746 --> 00:51:18.700
He was a Lieutenant-Colonel.

449
00:51:18.953 --> 00:51:21.553
His name is Custer.

450
00:51:21.654 --> 00:51:23.050
I know this name.

451
00:51:23.096 --> 00:51:25.541
He killed many warriors.

452
00:51:25.766 --> 00:51:27.847
Aye. Many warriors.

453
00:51:27.914 --> 00:51:29.674
So he was a good General.

454
00:51:29.789 --> 00:51:33.278
No. he wasn't a good General.
he was arrogant. foolhardy.

455
00:51:33.364 --> 00:51:36.802
and he got massacred because
he took a single battallion...

456
00:51:36.831 --> 00:51:38.033
...against 2.000 angry indians.

457
00:51:38.884 --> 00:51:42.578
2.000 indians?
How many men for Custer?

458
00:51:42.615 --> 00:51:48.064
- Two hundred eleven.
- I like this General Custer.

459
00:51:48.397 --> 00:51:51.860
He was a murderer.
who fell in love with his own legend.

460
00:51:52.465 --> 00:51:54.638
and his troopers died for it.

461
00:51:55.005 --> 00:51:56.872
I think this is a very good death.

462
00:51:56.989 --> 00:51:59.384
Oh. maybe you can
have one just like it someday.

463
00:51:59.408 --> 00:52:01.831
If it is my destiny.

464
00:52:01.960 --> 00:52:03.944
What you want from me?

465
00:52:03.990 --> 00:52:05.984
What do you want for yourself?

466
00:52:07.644 --> 00:52:08.989
What are you doing?

467
00:52:09.386 --> 00:52:12.217
Why are we having these conversations?

468
00:52:12.300 --> 00:52:15.015
What the hell am I doing here?

469
00:52:19.933 --> 00:52:25.531
In spring. the snow will melt
and passage will open.

470
00:52:26.884 --> 00:52:31.056
Until that time. you are here.

471
00:52:31.074 --> 00:52:34.167
Good day. Captain.

472
00:52:55.380 --> 00:52:59.634
1876... day unknown. month unknown.

473
00:53:01.310 --> 00:53:04.964
I continue to live among these unusual people.

474
00:53:06.232 --> 00:53:09.644
I'm a captive and I cannot escape.

475
00:53:11.208 --> 00:53:14.633
Mostly I'm treated with a kind of a mind of regret

476
00:53:14.831 --> 00:53:19.049
as if I was a street dog. an unwelcome guest.

477
00:53:31.336 --> 00:53:35.531
Everyone is polite.
everyone smiles and bows.

478
00:53:35.910 --> 00:53:41.346
But beneath this courtesy.
I detect their deep breath of moral feeling.

479
00:54:09.087 --> 00:54:10.787
Higen

480
00:54:20.688 --> 00:54:22.795
They are intriguing people.
